Growth Modeling

Tristan, Kyle

5/5/2021

1 Introduction

Population growth poses a challenge for many cities across the United States. Understanding where population growth will most likely occur is essential in understanding where to locate new development projects, where to locate public services, how to alter the zoning ordinance, and where urban growth boundaries should be located. Portland, Oregon is known for strict development regulations that concentrate the metropolitan region’s new development within urban growth boundaries. Within this study we explore where population and development will most likely grow in the Portland Metropolitan Area, and by how much.

The Portland Metropolitan Region consists of Clackamas County, Columbia County, Multnomah County, Washington County, Yamhill County, Clark County and Skamania County. Note that Clark County and Skamania County were excluded from the analysis since it is located in Washington State rather than Oregon. In the past few years, there has been talk about extending the metro lines regionally. For our analysis, we look at population projections in two different counties for the current scenario, and for the scenario where train lines are extended farther away from the city center.

mapTheme <- function(base_size = 12) {
  theme(
    text = element_text( color = "black"),
    plot.title = element_text(size = 14,colour = "black"),
    plot.subtitle=element_text(face="italic"),
    plot.caption=element_text(hjust=0),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),axis.title = element_blank(),
    axis.text = element_blank(),
    axis.title.x = element_blank(),
    axis.title.y = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill=NA, size=2)
  )
}

plotTheme <- function(base_size = 12) {
  theme(
    text = element_text( color = "black"),
    plot.title = element_text(size = 14,colour = "black"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(face="italic"),
    plot.caption = element_text(hjust=0),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.major = element_line("grey80", size = 0.1),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    panel.border = element_rect(colour = "black", fill=NA, size=2),

    legend.text = element_text(colour = "black", face = "italic"),

  )
}

1.1.1 Functions

#this function converts a column in to quintiles. It is used for mapping.
quintileBreaks <- function(df,variable) {
    as.character(quantile(df[[variable]],
                          c(.01,.2,.4,.6,.8),na.rm=T))
}

#This function can be used to convert a polygon sf to centroids xy coords.
xyC <- function(aPolygonSF) {
  as.data.frame(
    cbind(x=st_coordinates(st_centroid(aPolygonSF))[,1],
          y=st_coordinates(st_centroid(aPolygonSF))[,2]))
} 

#this function convert a raster to a data frame so it can be plotted in ggplot
rast <- function(inRaster) {
  data.frame(
    xyFromCell(inRaster, 1:ncell(inRaster)), 
    value = getValues(inRaster)) }

2.1 Portland Fishnet and Associated LCΔ

Development can be treated like a continuous surface; it is a land cover type that varies in intensity over space much like vegetation density. Creating grids allow us to model development over space.

  st_make_grid(OregonB, 2460.63) %>% # 984.252 ft = 300m    2952.76 = 900m 2640.64ft = 750m

nn_function <- function(measureFrom,measureTo,k) {
  #convert the sf layers to matrices
  measureFrom_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureFrom)
  measureTo_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureTo)
  nn <-   
    get.knnx(measureTo, measureFrom, k)$nn.dist
    output <-
    as.data.frame(nn) %>%
    rownames_to_column(var = "thisPoint") %>%
    gather(points, point_distance, V1:ncol(.)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>%
    group_by(thisPoint) %>%
    summarize(pointDistance = mean(point_distance)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>% 
    dplyr::select(-thisPoint) %>%
    pull()
  
  return(output)  
}

aggregateRaster <- function(inputRasterList, theFishnet) {
  #create an empty fishnet with the same dimensions as the input fishnet
  theseFishnets <- theFishnet %>% dplyr::select()
  #for each raster in the raster list
  for (i in inputRasterList) {
  #create a variable name corresponding to the ith raster
  varName <- names(i)
  #convert raster to points as an sf
    thesePoints <-
      rasterToPoints(i) %>%
      as.data.frame() %>%
      st_as_sf(coords = c("x", "y"), crs = st_crs(theFishnet)) %>%
      filter(.[[1]] == 1)
  #aggregate to the fishnet
    thisFishnet <-
      aggregate(thesePoints, theFishnet, length) %>%
      mutate(!!varName := ifelse(is.na(.[[1]]),0,1))
  #add to the larger fishnet
    theseFishnets <- cbind(theseFishnets,thisFishnet)
  }
  #output all aggregates as one large fishnet
   return(theseFishnets)
  }

theRasterList <- c(developed,forest,farm,wetlands,otherUndeveloped,water)

aggregatedRasters <-
  aggregateRaster(theRasterList, PortlandOMSA_fishnet) %>%
  dplyr::select(developed,forest,farm,wetlands,otherUndeveloped,water) %>%
  mutate_if(is.numeric,as.factor)

aggregatedRasters %>%
  gather(var,value,developed:water) %>%
  st_cast("POLYGON") %>%    #just to make sure no weird geometries slipped in
  mutate(X = xyC(.)$x,
         Y = xyC(.)$y) %>%

                        labels=c("Other","Land Cover"),
                        name = "") +
    labs(title = "Land cover types, 2001",
         subtitle = "As fishnet centroids") +
   mapTheme()

4 Model

Different models of development are compared. Each model uses different features. Model 1 uses the fewest features; only land cover data. Subsequent models incorporate more features, improving the R-squared each time. Model 8 had the best combination of features, producing the model with the highest R-Squared. In addition to land cover types, the best features included population change, highway distance, in/outside UGB, and distance to railways. Also defined here is the development scenario model (model 10) used later in this markdown.

4.6 Generalizability and Cross-Validation

spatialCV <- function(dataFrame, uniqueID, dependentVariable, modelName) {

#initialize a data frame 
endList <- list()

#create a list that is all the spatial group unqiue ids in the data frame (ie counties)    
  uniqueID_List <- unique(dataFrame[[uniqueID]])  
  x <- 1
  y <- length(uniqueID_List)
  
#create a counter and while it is less than the number of counties...  
  while(x <= y) 
  {
#call a current county    
    currentUniqueID <- uniqueID_List[x]
#create a training set comprised of units not in that county and a test set of units
#that are that county
    training <- dataFrame[ which(dataFrame[[uniqueID]] != uniqueID_List[x]),]
    testing <- dataFrame[ which(dataFrame[[uniqueID]] == uniqueID_List[x]),]
#create seperate xy vectors
    trainingX <- training[ , -which(names(training) %in% c(dependentVariable))]
    testingX <- testing[ , -which(names(testing) %in% c(dependentVariable))]
    
    trainY <- training[[dependentVariable]]
    testY <- testing[[dependentVariable]]
#Calculate predictions on the test county as part of a data frame including the observed
#outcome and the unique county ID    
   thisPrediction <- 
     data.frame(class = testY,
                probs = predict(modelName, testingX, type="response"),
                county = currentUniqueID) 

#Row bind the predictions to a data farme
   endList <- rbind(endList, thisPrediction)
#iterate counter    
    x <- x + 1 
  } 
#return the final list of counties and associated predictions  
  return (as.data.frame(endList))
}


spatialCV_counties <-
  spatialCV(dat,"Name","lc_change", Model8) %>%
  mutate(predClass = as.factor(ifelse(probs >= 0.17 ,1,0)))


spatialCV_metrics <-
  spatialCV_counties %>% 
    group_by(county) %>% 
    summarize(Observed_Change = sum(as.numeric(as.character(class))),
              Sensitivity = round(yardstick::sens_vec(class,predClass),2),
              Specificity = round(yardstick::spec_vec(class,predClass),2),
              Accuracy = round(yardstick::accuracy_vec(class,predClass),2)) 
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

  summarize(Total_Farmland = sum(farm11) / max(count),
            Total_Forest = sum(forest11) / max(count),
            Total_Wetlands = sum(wetlands11) / max(count),
            Total_Undeveloped = sum(otherUndeveloped11) / max(count),
            Sensitive_Land_Lost = sum(sensitive_lost11) / max(count),
            Sensitive_Regions = sum(sensitiveRegions) / max(count),
            Mean_Development_Demand = mean(Development_Demand)) %>%
  #get population data by county
  left_join(countyPopulation_2020 %>% 
            mutate(Population_Change = county_projection_2020 - county_population_2010,
                   Population_Change_Rate = Population_Change / county_projection_2020) %>%
            dplyr::select(Name,Population_Change_Rate))

county_specific_metrics %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -Name, -geometry.1) %>%
  mutate(Variable = factor(Variable, levels=c("Population_Change_Rate","Mean_Development_Demand",

                                              "Total_Wetlands","Sensitive_Land_Lost","Sensitive_Regions",
                                              ordered = TRUE))) %>%
  mutate(Planning_Designation = case_when(
    Variable == "Population_Change_Rate" | Variable == "Mean_Development_Demand" ~ "Demand-Side",

7 Conclusion

We believe our model is overall successful in predicting development demand and population growth. To predict development demand we looked at a variety of variables including distance to highways, land cover, urban growth boundary designation, public transportation and population. Our exploratory analysis indicates for greater development near public transportation, near highways, in urban growth boundaries and in highly populated areas. To model development, we used a binary logistical regression (binary logit) model by classifying each grid cell by either 1 or 0. 1 represents change to development land, and 0 represents everything else. The best features included population change, highway distance, in/outside UGB, and distance to railways. The McFadden R-Squared for this model was approximately 0.35. Overall, the model predicted development at 90% accuracy at a threshold 0.05. The true positive rate was 76% and the true negative rate was 90%. The model performed better identifying non-developed than developed areas. However, these areas are likely at risk for development.

Mapping our predictions, it appears that in the current scenario, development will continue to concentrate surrounding the Portland City Center within the urban growth boundary. Note that in the current scenario, transportation rail lines do not extend beyond the urban growth boundary. The counties experiencing the most population change are Multnomah, Washington and Clackamas. As expected, these counties are also where there is greater risk of development as predicted by the model. They are also the three counties that contain Portland and its environs.

We predicted development and population growth within Washington and Clackamas counties with an additional feature; distance to a fictional extension of the rail lines. We chose these two counties to look more closely at the impact of the hypothetical railway on different land types. For Washington, the land is more developed overall and has more farmland. Clackamas is less developed and contains a larger area of sensitive land, mainly forest. More than half of Clackamas is “sensitive”. The county is heavily wooded and contains a national forest. We created a development and population forecast using the model with the additional distance to fictional rail lines. Development tended to concentrate near the already-developed areas of Clackamas. The rail had a more significant impact on development in Washington County.
